{"timestamp":"2026-07-19T17:53:41.518Z","type":"event_msg","payload":{"type":"agent_message","message":"My take: yes—Portless is probably the cleanest long-term local solution, but I would adopt it in a separate follow-up rather than expand this merge repair.\n\nWhy it fits:\n\n- It gives the main checkout `https://evorto.localhost` and each worktree a stable branch subdomain such as `https://fix-ui.evorto.localhost`, while assigning internal ports automatically. That removes our need to register every generated port. [Portless README](https://github.com/vercel-labs/portless)\n- In the dev-only Auth0 application, we could register the exact main callback plus one wildcard worktree callback: `https://evorto.localhost/callback` and `https://*.evorto.localhost/callback`. Auth0 supports a wildcard in the left-most subdomain for first-party applications, one level only; it explicitly discourages this for production, which is fine for our isolated dev tenant. [Auth0 subdomain placeholders](https://auth0.com/docs/get-started/applications/wildcards-for-subdomains)\n- Default HTTPS also gives us behavior closer to staging and correct Secure/SameSite-cookie behavior. [Auth0 local HTTPS guidance](https://auth0.com/docs/libraries/secure-local-development)\n\nIt is not quite plug-and-play for this repo. We would need a small integration slice:\n\n- Teach the runtime generator to accept Portless’s injected `PORT` and `PORTLESS_URL`.\n- Treat `*.localhost` as loopback for our tenant-cookie fallback; currently only bare `localhost` qualifies.\n- Verify the proxy’s real `Host` and forwarded-proto behavior against our hardened request boundary.\n- Keep CI on its current exact `localhost:4200` origin; Portless is pre-1.0 and should not become a CI dependency.\n- Pin a tested Portless version and add source tests for the URL/runtime contract.\n\nSo: strong recommendation for local dev/worktrees, with the Auth0 wildcard restricted to the dev tenant. It should eliminate this entire class of port bookkeeping without weakening production callback rules.","phase":"commentary","memory_citation":null}}
{"timestamp":"2026-07-19T17:53:41.518Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"message","id":"msg_07acb54591783f13016a5d0f2076b881919d1085dca13db0b5","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"output_text","text":"My take: yes—Portless is probably the cleanest long-term local solution, but I would adopt it in a separate follow-up rather than expand this merge repair.\n\nWhy it fits:\n\n- It gives the main checkout `https://evorto.localhost` and each worktree a stable branch subdomain such as `https://fix-ui.evorto.localhost`, while assigning internal ports automatically. That removes our need to register every generated port. [Portless README](https://github.com/vercel-labs/portless)\n- In the dev-only Auth0 application, we could register the exact main callback plus one wildcard worktree callback: `https://evorto.localhost/callback` and `https://*.evorto.localhost/callback`. Auth0 supports a wildcard in the left-most subdomain for first-party applications, one level only; it explicitly discourages this for production, which is fine for our isolated dev tenant. [Auth0 subdomain placeholders](https://auth0.com/docs/get-started/applications/wildcards-for-subdomains)\n- Default HTTPS also gives us behavior closer to staging and correct Secure/SameSite-cookie behavior. [Auth0 local HTTPS guidance](https://auth0.com/docs/libraries/secure-local-development)\n\nIt is not quite plug-and-play for this repo. We would need a small integration slice:\n\n- Teach the runtime generator to accept Portless’s injected `PORT` and `PORTLESS_URL`.\n- Treat `*.localhost` as loopback for our tenant-cookie fallback; currently only bare `localhost` qualifies.\n- Verify the proxy’s real `Host` and forwarded-proto behavior against our hardened request boundary.\n- Keep CI on its current exact `localhost:4200` origin; Portless is pre-1.0 and should not become a CI dependency.\n- Pin a tested Portless version and add source tests for the URL/runtime contract.\n\nSo: strong recommendation for local dev/worktrees, with the Auth0 wildcard restricted to the dev tenant. It should eliminate this entire class of port bookkeeping without weakening production callback rules."}],"phase":"commentary","internal_chat_message_metadata_passthrough":{"turn_id":"019f7b3b-61db-7f22-b04f-a7cc62c9b8f9"}}}
